v class=3D"text-formatting"><p>In the same way that simple font changes on =
a restaurant menu or newspaper <strong>increase the perception of value and=
 legibility</strong>, so can font changes on your landing page or website.<=
/p><p>Are you asking why Times New Roman didn=E2=80=99t make the list? Beca=
use we=E2=80=99re tired of it. It=E2=80=99s dated. <a href=3D"https://mediu=
m.com/@peterswriting/why-i-stopped-using-times-new-roman-and-why-you-should=
-too-367afef500fc" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">Use someth=
ing else.</a>&nbsp;</p><p>Choose one of the fonts above. Or two of them=E2=
=80=94and test them out.</p></div><h3 id=3D"h-how-to-figure-out-a-font">How=
 to figure out a font </h3><div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>Sometimes you =
see a font on a webpage when you=E2=80=99re surfing around, and you love it=
. But how do you know what that font is so you can use it on your own site?=
&nbsp;</p><p>Easy.&nbsp;</p><p><a href=3D"https://chrome.google.com/webstor=
e/detail/whatfont/jabopobgcpjmedljpbcaablpmlmfcogm/related?hl=3Den" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">Install WhatFont</a> Chrome extensi=
on. Used by over 1 million happy customers, you simply click on <strong><em=
>f?</em></strong> Symbol on your Chrome bar and then click on the font in q=
uestion.</p></div><div><figure class=3D"wp-block-image"><img height=3D"732"=
 width=3D"1600" loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://wp.klientboost.com/wp-conte=
nt/uploads/2021/07/img_61005e135db95.png" alt=3D"WhatFont tells you the nam=
e of the font as well as the style, weight, size, line height, and color"><=
figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption"><a href=3D"https://chrome.google.co=
m/webstore/detail/whatfont/jabopobgcpjmedljpbcaablpmlmfcogm/related?hl=3Den=
" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">WhatFont</a> tells you the =
name of the font as well as the style, weight, size, line height, and color=
</figcaption></figure></div><div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>If you=E2=80=
=99re lucky, it will be a Google Font, and you can rest assured it will loo=
k nice on your website when you install it and use it.</p></div><h2 id=3D"h=
-seven-more-in-depth-tips-on-landing-page-and-website-fonts">Seven more in-=
depth tips on landing page and website fonts </h2><div class=3D"text-format=
ting"><p>You get it. Landing page and website fonts are essential.</p><p>Bu=
t we=E2=80=99re going to dissect the different font elements <strong>you ca=
n test</strong> in your headlines and copy to <strong>improve conversion ra=
tes</strong>.</p></div><h3 id=3D"h-font-color">Font color </h3><div class=
=3D"text-formatting"><p>Just like button colors affect conversion rates, so=
 do font colors.</p><p>Years ago, the Gmail team tested 40 different shades=
 of blue to measure <a href=3D"https://klientboost.com/landing-pages/click-=
through-pages/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">click-through=
</a> rates on Gmail buttons. Bing ran a similar blue font color test on the=
ir search results page.</p><p>The result was an astounding <strong>$80 mill=
ion in </strong><a href=3D"http://www.cnet.com/news/behind-bings-blue-links=
/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener"><strong>additional annual =
revenue</strong></a>.</p><p>For the test, it turned out that<strong> font c=
ontrast and color contributed more to reading performance</strong> than the=
 typeface.</p><p>Bing switched from Arial to Verdana, but ultimately switch=
ed back to Arial because it performed better.</p></div><h3 id=3D"h-font-siz=
e">Font size </h3><div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>Readability and legibil=
ity depend largely on font size.</p><p>What font size is best for online re=
aders?</p><p>There is some debate here, but <a href=3D"https://learnui.desi=
gn/blog/mobile-desktop-website-font-size-guidelines.html" target=3D"_blank"=
 rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">16px</a> is a winner for body copy for both mo=
bile and desktop.</p><p>Different screen sizes have different resolutions. =
Your headline (H1) should be several sizes bigger than your subheadlines (H=
2, H3, H4, etc.), and your subheadlines should be several sizes bigger than=
 supporting copy.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>But bigger isn=E2=80=99t always better.=
&nbsp;</p><p>Overdo it, and you end up shouting at your customers and pulli=
ng circus more than serious.</p></div><h4 id=3D"h-here-s-what-we-use-for-kl=
ientboost-blog-articles">Here=E2=80=99s what we use for KlientBoost blog ar=
ticles: </h4><div class=3D"text-formatting"><ul><li>H1: 50px&nbsp;</li><li>=
H2: 32px</li><li>H3: 25px</li><li>P: 18px</li></ul></div><h3 id=3D"h-font-t=
ype">Font type </h3><div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>The type of fonts mak=
es <strong>dramatic importance</strong> on how easily someone skims your la=
nding page or website. A Microsoft and an MIT student <a href=3D"http://aff=
ect.media.mit.edu/pdfs/05.larson-picard.pdf" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noref=
errer noopener">tested typography </a>on mood and cognitive performance (th=
e ability to process and understand information).</p><p>They decided to spl=
it up the participants between bad and good typography.&nbsp;</p><p>The goo=
d typography had a large font for the heading and white space in the margin=
s. The document was left justified and there was proper font and line spaci=
ng. The bad typography didn=E2=80=99t; the title was only a couple of sizes=
 bigger than the body copy and it was underlined. There was minimal space b=
etween the heading and the body copy, and there was hardly any line-height =
(the amount of space between the lines). The entire document was full-width=
 justified leaving awkward spaces between some words.</p><p>The results? Th=
e <strong>good typography group finished 52% of the task,</strong> while th=
e bad typography group could only finish 48% of the task.</p></div><h3 id=
=3D"h-font-weight">Font weight </h3><div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>You s=
hould be a freaking pro when it comes to landing page and website fonts, ty=
pefaces, and typography by now.</p><p>But here=E2=80=99s another one I=E2=
=80=99ll throw at you: font-weight.</p><p>The width and relative =E2=80=9Ct=
hickness=E2=80=9D (medium or bold) of your main header (H1) and subheaders =
(H2, H3, etc.) should be bigger than your body copy.&nbsp;</p><p>How much b=
igger?</p><p>A quick rule of thumb is to multiply by 2. Choose your body co=
py font size first (say, 18px) and multiply by 2 for your heading (36px).&n=
bsp;</p><p>Grain of salt; overall size depends on the fonts used.&nbsp;</p>=
<p>Another guideline is to use the Fibonacci sequence (e.g. 16 =E2=80=93 24=
 =E2=80=93 40 =E2=80=93 64 =E2=80=93 104) to produce a natural progression =
of headlines and pleasing typographic results. Using the Fibonacci sequence=
, your body copy would be 16px, your H3s would be 24px, your H2s would be 4=
0px, and your H1 would be 64px. If that works for the font you chose, use i=
t.</p><p>At KlientBoost, we use Open Sans typeface for our blog articles. F=
or the H1, we use Open Sans Bold with a size of 50px. Our body copy is Open=
 Sans Regular with a size of 18px.&nbsp;</p><p>Why did we make our H1 so mu=
ch bigger than our body copy? If the rule is to multiply by 2, our H1 shoul=
d be 36px in size.</p><p>Two reasons:&nbsp;</p><ol><li>We use the gambit of=
 SEO hierarchies to give Google a good understanding of our copy structure=
=E2=80=94right down to the H5 heading. Because we use six hierarchies (H1-H=
5 and the body copy, P), we differentiate those headings with an appreciabl=
e size difference. To do that, our H1 ended up being bigger than the rule o=
f thumb multiplier.</li><li>It looks good. Rule of thumbs are general rules=
. Use them to get in the ballpark. Then break them for home runs.</li></ol>=
<p>Last font-weight point: <strong>use bold body copy</strong> throughout y=
our document to emphasize specific heavyweight points.</p></div><h3 id=3D"h=
-line-spacing">Line spacing </h3><div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>Remember=
 that time in college when your paper had to be 24 pages, but you couldn=E2=
=80=99t squeeze out more than 20?</p><p>Line space to the rescue!</p><p>But=
 seriously, line spacing makes lines of copy easier to read. It creates whi=
te space, a best practices UX law, chunking your copywriting into more easi=
ly digestible blocks.&nbsp;</p><p>To increase your conversion rates, play a=
round with line spacing.</p><p>A line-height somewhere between 1.5em to 1.8=
em works well for regular body copy. The <strong>em</strong> demarcation is=
 a CSS element that denotes the relationship between font size and the spac=
e between the lines.</p><p>If a paragraph has a font size of 18px, using a =
common line-height of 1.5 means there is about 27px of space between the li=
nes (18px x 1.5 =3D 27px). This ratio improves readability.</p><p>We use a =
font size of 18px and a line-height of 32px. Does that follow the rule? Pre=
tty much. We add in a few more pixel points of space.&nbsp;</p></div><div><=
figure class=3D"wp-block-image"><img height=3D"1000" width=3D"1432" loading=
=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://wp.klientboost.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/img_=
61005e144d26e.png" alt=3D"A pleasing line height (the space between lines) =
makes for a better user experience =E2=80=93 source"><figcaption class=3D"w=
p-element-caption">A pleasing line height (the space between lines) makes f=
or a better user experience =E2=80=93 <a href=3D"http://unbounce.com/conver=
sion-rate-optimization/5-conversion-studies/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"nore=
ferrer noopener">source</a></figcaption></figure></div><div class=3D"text-f=
ormatting"><p>Line height makes paragraphs easier to read. But your copywri=
ting skills decide whether the visitor likes what they=E2=80=99re reading.<=
/p></div><h3 id=3D"h-line-width">Line width </h3><div class=3D"text-formatt=
ing"><p>According to the UX law of common region, always leave a border aro=
und an element or group of elements to help readers=E2=80=99 brains associa=
te commonality between those items.&nbsp;&nbsp;</p><p>In other words, leave=
 a white border around your copy and whitespace between paragraphs to separ=
ate thoughts into readable chunks for better comprehension.&nbsp;</p><p>Don=
=E2=80=99t run copy from the left edge of the page, across the page, to the=
 right edge. Eyes and brains don=E2=80=99t like that.</p></div><div><figure=
 class=3D"wp-block-image is-resized"><img loading=3D"lazy" src=3D"https://w=
p.klientboost.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/img_61005e14cdb38.png" alt=3D"=
Leave a whitespace border around copy =E2=80=93 source " width=3D"704" heig=
ht=3D"556"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Leave a whitespace bord=
er around copy =E2=80=93 <a href=3D"https://lawsofux.com/law-of-common-regi=
on/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">source</a> </figcaption>=
</figure></div><div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>If you go too wide, then p=
eople will have a hard time focusing on the text. If you go too narrow, the=
n you may break the readers=E2=80=99 rhythm.</p><p>The science goes like th=
is: <a href=3D"https://lawsofux.com/law-of-common-region/" target=3D"_blank=
" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">Gestalt laws of grouping </a>observe that hum=
ans naturally perceive objects in organized patterns (this is called Pr=C3=
=A4gnanz). The mind is disposed to make groups out of chaos based on proxim=
ity, similarity, continuity, closure, and connectedness.</p></div><div><fig=
ure class=3D"wp-block-image"><img height=3D"300" width=3D"500" loading=3D"l=
azy" src=3D"https://wp.klientboost.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/img_61005=
e1662eec.png" alt=3D"The safer bet is to go narrow to begin with =E2=80=93 =
source"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">The safer bet is to go nar=
row to begin with =E2=80=93 <a href=3D"http://uxmovement.com/content/how-ma=
rgins-and-line-lengths-affect-user-reading/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noref=
errer noopener">source</a></figcaption></figure></div><div class=3D"text-fo=
rmatting"><p>Optimal line width for your landing page or website copy shoul=
d be about 50-60 characters per line.</p><p>Test out any long copy you have=
 by messing around with the widths, and use a tool like <a href=3D"https://=
www.crazyegg.com/heatmap" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">Cra=
zyEgg</a> to measure <strong>how far down visitors scroll</strong> before a=
nd after your changes.</p></div><h3 id=3D"h-line-breaks">Line breaks </h3><=
div class=3D"text-formatting"><p>Line breaks are similar to line widths. Th=
ey also make it <strong>easier and quicker</strong> for your visitors to re=
ad and understand your copy when used correctly.</p></div><div><figure clas=
s=3D"wp-block-image"><img height=3D"300" width=3D"500" loading=3D"lazy" src=
=3D"https://wp.klientboost.com/wp-content/uploads/2021/07/img_61005e16879e7=
.png" alt=3D"Are your sentences rhythm roadblocks? &nbsp;=E2=80=93 source">=
<figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Are your sentences rhythm roadbloc=
ks? &nbsp;=E2=80=93 <a href=3D"http://uxmovement.com/content/how-margins-an=
d-line-lengths-affect-user-reading/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer no=
opener">source</a></figcaption></figure></div><div class=3D"text-formatting=
"><p>Give your sentences breathing room to give your conversions the best c=
hances of happening.</p><p>We do this a lot in our KlientBoost articles. Yo=
u=E2=80=99ve probably noticed that we use a lot of one-line paragraphs in o=
ur writing. That=E2=80=99s not what we are taught in school, but it=E2=80=
=99s what we have tested works best.</p></div><h2 id=3D"h-the-secret-cro-in=
gredients">The secret CRO ingredients </h2><div class=3D"text-formatting"><=
p>Wow! Quite the rundown on fonts and their psychological impacts, huh?</p>=
<p><em>Don=E2=80=99t sweat the small stuff</em> doesn=E2=80=99t apply to la=
nding page and webite fonts. Sweating the basic rules of typefaces, fonts, =
and typography makes a <strong>big performance impact</strong> when it come=
s to conversions.</p><p>There is no right or wrong font if you choose from =
the Google Font list we provided above=E2=80=94all of those work great for =
web applications. But whatever you pick, be sure to test the result.</p><p>=
As you go through this and start testing fonts, remember that the best land=
ing page or website font choices are ones where visitors don=E2=80=99t noti=
ce the font <a href=3D"https://visual.ly/serif-vs-sans-final-battle" target=
=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener">but do understand the message</a>.<=
/p><p>What landing page fonts have you used to improve performance?</p><p>N=
ow that you have fonts down, check out these 34 <a href=3D"https://klientbo=
ost.com/landing-pages/landing-page-best-practices/" target=3D"_blank" rel=
